Jubilee Holdings&rsquo; half year net profits increased to Sh1.87 billion compared to Sh1.57 billion the previous year on the back of increased revenues in all sectors.The pretax profits went up 19 per cent to settle at Sh2.34 billion up from Sh1.97 billion recorded last year.The half year results released yesterday shows that the firm&rsquo;s underwriting results grew by 23 per cent to stand at Sh1.1 billion. Gross premiums and contributions grew 8 per cent to stand at Sh18.6 billion.Subsequently, earning per share rose to Sh26 compared to Sh23 last year, an increase of 23 per cent.Total incomes recorded a 30 per cent jump to stand at Sh14.89 billion an aspect attributed to a good run at the Nairobi Securities Exchange (NSE) that saw a 13 per cent growth in the first 6 months of 2017.&lsquo;&rsquo;These impressive results were realized in an unpredictable business environment, currency volatility both in the regional and global market, as well as regulatory changes,&rsquo;&rsquo; said Mr Nizar Juma chairman, Jubilee Holdings.Jubilee Holdings&rsquo; assets now stands at Sh101.1 billion, a 15 per cent increase from Sh87.6 billion&lsquo;&rsquo;Our balance sheet is a clear indication of our financial strength and ability to protect the interests of our insured community. By leveraging on our strengths,we remain focused on our goals to grow and expand in the region,&rsquo;&rsquo; said Juma.The insurers&rsquo; long term businesses grew from Sh5.2 billion to Sh6.6 billion during the first six months of 2017, a 26 per cent improvement.